36. capsula: te. scrinium.

37. mente maligna, etc, in gruaging temper or ungrocious spirit.

39. non: modifying the entire expression, though placed before the pronoun, as frequently in Catul- lus. Riese gives a full list of such phrases. — utriusque: i.e. of verses composed especially for you at this time, and also of earlier verses.

40. ultro ego deferrem, ete: Catullus had apparently known of the sorrow of Manlius before his letter carne, but because of his own grief had taken no notice of it till personally appealed to.

41. non possum reticere: the earnestness of the poet's feeling is well expressed by the abruptness of the opening, carried out by the emphatic repetition of iuuerit.- deae: the poem opens, in epic style, withan address to the Muses; cf. Theocr. 17 (the panegyrie upon Ptolemy).
